## ACTIVE FORESHADOWING

- The guild’s data shows a systemic void: trained solvers die on Grade 2 at a rate untrained civilians do not. The institution will soon have to confront that its methods are training the wrong approach.
- The Dakar gate’s solution rested on a property invisible when objects were handled one at a time—a structural relationship. This is the first explicit instance of “related problem” solving, and it will recur as the core of Arc 2.
- The unnamed woman who solved the Dakar gate had also closed a gate in Kumasi two weeks earlier. Her existence, and her silence, hints at a network of silent solvers the guild cannot track.
- The mystery person’s taxonomy of wrong approaches (executor, system builder, information gatherer) matches the guild’s observed failure modes, but the guild has no name for them. The junior clerk’s discovery of the pages will likely resurface once the guild’s crisis deepens.
- Kuuku Dadzie’s failure as a confident specialist is duplicated in microcosm in the guild’s own training method: treat every gate as an isolated problem, never ask “what does this remind me of?” That institutional blindness is the hidden antagonist of Arc 2.
- The ordinary-life echoes in Chapter 7 (Yejide asking “what’s missing?” on the inspection floor, Kwabena spotting the routing gap, Wanjiku ignoring categories to trace dates, Fatou asking what was missing from the original survey) confirm that the process transfers even when the solvers do not consciously connect it to gates. The next step is for them to recognise the pattern consciously.
- The anchor’s Dakar page records the moment the unnamed solver sat down. The notation is more precise than earlier entries—suggesting the anchor is refining their observation method, possibly building toward a prediction model.

